<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
Species were obtained from the hindgut lining of 
<taxonomicName family="Leuctridae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="family">Leuctridae</taxonomicName>
nymphs (mainly 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Leuctridae" genus="Leuctra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leuctra hippopus" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippopus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Leuctra hippopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). We found several thalli, most of them producing trichospores and one also bearing helicoidal zygospores, formed homothallically, measuring 25-27 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.5-6.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, growing on a fusiform zygosporophore measuring 20-23 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7-8.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, with a 3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long supporting cell and a sigmoid or reflexed intermediate cell about 20-24 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long in the specimens seen (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">24</figureCitation>
). All the characteristics of spores and accompanying cells fit those of the specimens reported from other localities in Europe, including Spain (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" author="Santamaria, S" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="174 - 178" refId="B48" refString="Santamaria, S, Girbal, J, 1998. Two new species of Orphella from Spain. Mycological Research 102: 174 - 178, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" title="Two new species of Orphella from Spain." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0953756297004607" volume="102" year="1998">Santamaria and Girbal 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1335 - 1347" refId="B66" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2005. Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella. Mycologia 97: 1335 - 1347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" title="Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" volume="97" year="2005">Valle and Santamaria 2005</bibRefCitation>
), Norway (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="891 - 910" refId="B72" refString="White, MM, Lichtwardt, RW, 2004. Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae. Mycologia 96: 891 - 910, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" title="Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" volume="96" year="2004">White and Lichtwardt 2004</bibRefCitation>
); Italy (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="712 - 727" refId="B67" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2013. New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 105: 712 - 727, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" title="New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" volume="105" year="2013">Valle et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Thallus has the characteristic basal cell (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">25</figureCitation>
) and lateral subsidiary branches.
</paragraph>
